# Queries Explanation
### Farmer Produce & Market Supply Chain Management System — 31383_2025_Valentin_Farm_DB

This document explains, in plain language, what each significant query in the project does, which tables it touches, and why it matters to the business.
Use this alongside the Live Demonstration Script when explaining query execution to an examiner.

---

## 1. Revenue by Buyer

```sql
SELECT b.buyer_name, SUM(s.quantity_sold * s.unit_price) AS total_revenue
FROM sale s
JOIN buyer b ON s.buyer_id = b.buyer_id
GROUP BY b.buyer_name
ORDER BY total_revenue DESC;
```

**What it does:** Joins `SALE` to `BUYER` so each sale row is linked to the buyer who made it, multiplies quantity by unit price to get revenue per sale, then totals
that per buyer and ranks buyers from highest to lowest revenue.

**Why it matters:** Tells the cooperative which buyers are worth prioritizing relationships with — directly answers one of the Phase I 
  objectives ("insight into which buyer offers the best price").

---

## 2. Harvest Detail Listing

```sql
SELECT f.full_name, c.crop_name, h.quantity, h.quality_grade
FROM harvest h
JOIN farm f ON h.farm_id = f.farm_id
JOIN crop c ON h.crop_id = c.crop_id
ORDER BY h.harvest_date;
```

**What it does:** A three-way join across `HARVEST`, `FARM`, and `CROP` that turns internal foreign-key IDs into human-readable output — 
  the farmer's name and the crop's name — for every harvest, ordered chronologically.

**Why it matters:** This is the query a cooperative clerk would run to see "who delivered what, and how much" without needing to look up ID numbers manually.

