## 7. Explicit Cursor Query (Unpaid Sales, PL/SQL)

```sql
CURSOR c_unpaid IS
    SELECT s.sale_id, b.buyer_name, s.quantity_sold, s.unit_price,
           (s.quantity_sold * s.unit_price) AS total_due
    FROM sale s JOIN buyer b ON s.buyer_id = b.buyer_id
    WHERE s.sale_id NOT IN (SELECT sale_id FROM payment);
```

**What it does:** Same logic as query 3, but declared as an explicit cursor inside `farm_pkg.list_unpaid_sales`, so it can be opened, fetched row-by-row, 
 and printed via `DBMS_OUTPUT` — demonstrating procedural row-level control rather than a single set-based result.

**Why it matters:** Satisfies the PL/SQL programming requirement to demonstrate an explicit cursor, while still solving a genuine business need 
  (a printable list of outstanding payments).

